       <h1>Staying Safe While Traveling</h1>
       <img src="https://hype.my/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/Girl-Looking-At-Map.jpg" height = 400px/>
  </div>
<h2>1. Be mindful of pick pocketing or other distraction scams</h2>
<p><h3>If you have a backpack and you are on a bus or train, keep it front of you. Don't keep your wallet in your back pocket or any valuables. Be wary of people “bumping” into you. Bumping distracts you from realizing your valuables are missing.</h3></p>
<h2>2. Be cautious of driving in a taxi/driving services</h2>
<p><h3>Do research on which driving service you will take. Check for identification for the driver and the service, especially if you take a ride from a service you do not know of. It is better to use official taxis.</h3></p>
<h2>3. Keep valuables out of sight</h2>
<p><h3>When you lock your vehicle, make sure your items are hidden. Also, hide your valuables especially when you are on the beach.</h3></p>
<h2>4. Blend in</h2>
<p><h3>Do not show your wealth because this can make you an easy target for being robbed. Learn to pick some of the local dialect so communication can be easier. Do not advertise U.S. opinions or other political opinions.</h3></p>
<h2>5. Ask identification in doubt</h2>
<p><h3>Sometimes people in other countries  can impersonate a police officer or other authority. They can possibly rob you, or have other bad intentions. Always ask for identification. If you have suspicions, ask the officer to escort you to the police station to check legitimacy.</h3></p>
<h2>6. Be wary of using an ATM</h2>
<p><h3>An ATM skimming is created when thieves put a device inside the slot of an ATM. THis device blocks your card from going into a machine, and instead retrieves information of your card. Feel the slot of the ATM for a tab, or other odd things.</h3></p>
<h2>7. Write down emergency information of the place you are Traveling in</h2>
<p><h3>If you write down emergency contact information, you do not have to worry about scrambling for help during a dire situation.</h3></p>
<h2>8. Avoid booking scams </h2>
<p><h3>Do not judge a book by its cover, or in this case, the picture of the residency or resort. This is how scammers lure people in! Make sure to check for legitimacy of the place you are booking.</h3></p> 

